observations.recommendation:
Moreover, we recommended and Management agreed to:
Create a Disposal and Appraisal Committee (DAC);
Require the supply officer to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) and submit a copy of the same to the Audit Team and DAC for inspection;
Require the DAC to prepare the Appraisal Review Report on Property for Disposal (ARRPD) showing the appraised values of the assets and submit a copy of the same to the Audit Team for review; and
Instruct DAC to convene and agree on the mode of disposal of the items after receiving the ARRPD, duly reviewed by the audit team, and recommend the applicable mode of disposal for Municipal Mayor’s approval and submit these documents to the Audit Team for evaluation and action thereon prior to the disposal of unserviceable items.

We recommended and:
The Human Resource Management Officer and other concerned officials agreed to ensure that the JO personnel reflect their actual work schedule in the DTRs to ensure the reliability and validity of the documents;
The Municipal Accountant agreed to ensure the completeness of supporting documents before claims are processed as provided in COA Circular No. 2012-001; and
Management agreed to strictly adhere to the policies and guidelines in the hiring of personnel under contract of services and/or job orders as provided for in CSC Memorandum Circular No. 40, series of 1998.

Management provided the following written comments and action plan on the noted observations:
Issuance of an office order for the procurement of Biometrics System Device and hiring of IT personnel to oversee and manage the implementation of the system;
Pending the implementation of biometric recording of attendance, an office order will be issued for the submission of DTRs together with the authenticated copy of logbooks to the HRMO;
Submission will be per Office/Unit together with the authenticated copy of the logbooks. After assessment and recording of said documents, the same will be forwarded to the approving authority;
The HRMO, in coordination with other concerned LGU offices, will take the lead in the formulation of internal policies, guidelines, and standards in the hiring of the Job Order (JO) and Contract of Service (COS) personnel to ensure judicious and reasonable utilization of public funds subject to the approval of the Local Chief Executive and Sangguniang Bayan; and
Close and daily monitoring on personnel assisting RCC will be enhance to ensure accountability and efficient and effective system of collection.

We recommended, and the MDRRMO agreed to:
ensure that the prior year’s unexpended LDRRMF is included in the LDRRMFIP in the ensuing year in accordance with COA Circular No. 2012-001, and;
prepare a revised LDRRMIP for the release and utilization of new expenditure items under the LDRRMF upon the recommendation of the MDRRMC.

We reiterated and the Local Chief Executive agreed, being the chair of the Local Development Council, spearheads the appropriate planning of priority development projects to optimize the utilization of the fund and ensure that PPAs are well-planned and procurement-and implementation-ready as mandated by laws and regulations.

During the exit conference, Management conveyed to following comments and action plan:
Based on the schedule of unimplemented PPAs presented, majority of the identified projects were unimplemented due to the following factors:
Delays in the issuance/submission of procurement request forms from end-user units;
Revision of detailed engineering design and program of works;
Lack of Environmental Permit/Clearance for 1 project (initially identified as outside the protected area but was later on determined as a project within an environmentally-critical area, hence the need for additional environmental permit/clearance);
Projects included in the Supplemental appropriations were approved on the latter part of the year, hence the delay in implementation; and
Most of the projects identified were actually implemented, however, completed and billed only in the current year.
Moving forward, the LCE and the Management, through the Municipal Development Council and other concerned departments/offices shall endeavor to:
Strengthen local project monitoring to ensure that identified development projects are delivered within the fiscal year or the approved period of implementation;
Reinforce PPA planning and investment programming through a more thorough evaluation of proposed PPAs with the goal of ensuring that identified programs and projects are well-planned and procurement-and-implementation ready;
Prioritize higher-value projects — improve efficiency as this will reduce the number of projects to be implemented and effect higher-value impacts and benefits to the constituents; and
Cluster similar and/or complementary projects to improve efficiency in the preparation of plans and designs, procurement, and implementation.
As a rejoinder, Management was reminded on the requirement that projects and programs shall be well-planned, procurement-and-implementation-ready in order that the target beneficiaries obtain the full socio-economic benefits they could have derived if the project had been fully implemented.

We recommended, and the Municipal Mayor, through the LSB agreed to:
Obtain the CY 2024 quarterly and annual reports of the SEF Budget Accountability Form No. 1 (Annex B) on SEF utilization prepared by the Municipal Accountant;
Prepare a transmittal letter and submit the said reports to the DepEd CO, through appropriate channels copy furnished the Sangguniang Bayan and the Regional Offices of the DBM and the DILG;
Immediately post the CY 2024 SEF utilization reports in at least three (3) conspicuous public places; and
Faithfully comply with the submission requirement and full disclosure policy of the DILG in compliance with of Section 6 of the DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 2017-1.

The Accountant, during the exit conference, stated that the SEF Utilization Reports are already posted on the LGUs FDP Boards and online on the DILG FDP Website. He also conveyed Management’s commitment to regularly submit the required reports with the DEPED, DBM and DILG.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Accountant -

prepare the necessary adjustments corresponding to the noted accounting errors and omissions based on relevant and sufficient documents;

coordinate closely with the Municipal Treasurer for the regular reconciliation of records; and

inform the depository banks in writing of the reconciling items that need to be adjusted in their records;

Municipal Treasurer coordinate with the Municipal Accountant for the regular reconciliation of records.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
1. Require the Municipal Accountant to make necessary adjustments on the
proper recognition of the BGCM and also, adjust the misclassified
accounts in the books of the LGU;
2. Require the Municipal Budget Officer and Accountant to reconcile their
records on the proper charging of expenses within the authorized
supplemental budget;
3. Direct the MPDC to prepare and submit supplemental AIP;
4. Require the BAC Chairman to undertake procurement process in
accordance with the approved annual procurement plan;
5. Require the Local Finance Committee (LFC) to prepare and submit
monthly fund utilization reports using the format in Annex C of DBM
LBC No. 125;
6. Require the posting of accumulated reports on the LGU’s website and
post the same in at least three (3) conspicuous public places for
transparency.
